- OK.

31
00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:36,760
- A frame full of bees.

32
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:40,000
He's got his gloves on, he's got his
beekeeper's outfit on.

33
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,000
- OK. It's painted on a... On stone.
- It's stone.

34
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:44,960
I got it from a hardware store.

35
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:47,680
I think it's probably some sort of
man-made...

36
00:01:47,680 --> 00:01:51,720
- Yeah. It's concrete. Why is it so
worn out?

37
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:54,400
- He was so proud of it when I gave it
to him,

38
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:56,680
that he put it outside...
- Oh.

39
00:01:56,680 --> 00:01:59,320
- ..by his front door for almost 12
years.

40
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:02,440
It got a lot of rain, it got a lot of
snow,

41
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:05,000
so naturally, it's just deteriorated
over time.

42
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,480
- What was your dad's name?

43
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:08,000
- David Julian Clune.

44
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,480
- Was he professionally a beekeeper,
or was it like a big hobby?

45
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:13,000
- It was a big hobby.

46
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,360
So he was a reverend.

47
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:17,520
When this was taken he was a curate.

48
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:21,080
A lot of people found him very
approachable and very warm.

49
00:02:21,080 --> 00:02:23,680
And I think he liked the parallels
between beekeeping

50
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:27,280
and church because, I guess, like,
colonies are like a congregation

51
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:28,960
in a way.

52
00:02:28,960 --> 00:02:31,040
- So how many bees did he have?

53
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:34,800
- Oh, at any one time he could have up
to 20,000-30,000 bees

54
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:37,080
in a really strong colony.
- Really?!
- Yeah.

55
00:02:37,080 --> 00:02:39,600
A lot of bees.
- A huge amount of honey.

56
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:40,960
- The most rewarding part

57
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:42,480
for him was harvesting the honey

58
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:44,200
because he would sell it at the front
door,

59
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:46,360
and then he would donate a part of
that money to the church.

60
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:49,040
- Did it catch on with you? Were you
interested in bees?

61
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:51,000
- Yeah. When my husband and I bought
our own home,

62
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:53,240
I said to my dad, "I want some bees."

63
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:55,200
And he gave me my first colony.

64
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:58,640
- So you kept this going, then? You're
a beekeeper yourself?
- Yeah.

65
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:01,000
I think bees are such interesting
creatures.

66
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:03,200
When you go into the hive, you can
smell the honey,

67
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:04,920
you can smell the wax.

68
00:03:04,920 --> 00:03:07,360
You can hear the gentle humming of the
bees.

69
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:10,520
It's absolutely intoxicating.

70
00:03:10,520 --> 00:03:13,200
It really, really does feel like being
at one with nature,

71
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:16,280
quite literally. It's just incredible.

72
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:17,720
I know he felt like that.

73
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:21,640
- Why have you chosen to have this
looked at now?

74
00:03:21,640 --> 00:03:25,760
- Four and a half months ago, he
passed away very suddenly

75
00:03:25,760 --> 00:03:28,440
and very unexpectedly of
bronchopneumonia.

76
00:03:28,440 --> 00:03:32,680
- Oh. That's really recent. That must
have been quite a shock.

77
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:34,040
- Yeah, it was.
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

78
00:03:36,200 --> 00:03:39,360
But five or six weeks after he passed
away,

79
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:40,840
my husband and I found out

80
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:43,880
that we were expecting our first
